        <!-- ——————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————
             Lesson 1: What Is Homeostasis?
             —————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— -->
        <section id="lesson-1" class="content-section fade-in-up">
          <nav class="lesson-inline-nav" aria-label="Lesson navigation">
            <span class="lesson-inline-nav__current">Lesson 1 of 2</span>
            <a href="#lesson-2" class="lesson-inline-nav__link lesson-inline-nav__link--next">
              Lesson 2: Examples of Homeostasis
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M3 8h10M9 4l4 4-4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </a>
          </nav>

          <h2>Lesson 1: What Is Homeostasis?</h2>

          <p class="section-intro">
            You are about to begin a new standard — <strong>AS 91604</strong>, one of the most
            conceptually elegant topics in Level 3 Biology. The central question is deceptively
            simple: how does an animal keep its internal conditions stable, even when the
            outside world is constantly changing? The answer to that question — homeostasis —
            underlies almost every organ system you will study for the rest of the year.
          </p>

          <div class="internal-note">
            <svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M12 8v1M12 12v4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            <div>
              <strong>Internal Assessment:</strong> AS 91604 is assessed internally — through a
              written report you submit to your teacher, not a timed exam. The practice tasks in
              this unit are designed to build the explanatory writing skills your assessor will
              be looking for.
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Definition ── -->
          <h3>Defining Homeostasis</h3>

          <p>
            <strong>Homeostasis</strong> is the process by which an organism maintains a
            <strong>stable internal environment</strong> despite changes in external conditions.
            The word comes from the Greek <em>homeo</em> (similar/same) and <em>stasis</em>
            (standing still). It was coined by American physiologist <strong>Walter Bradford
            Cannon</strong> in 1926.
          </p>

          <div class="definition-box">
            <div class="definition-box__label">Core Definition</div>
            <p>
              Homeostasis is the <strong>maintenance of a relatively constant internal
              environment</strong> through physiological mechanisms that detect and correct
              deviations from a <strong>set point</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p>
            The key word here is <em>relatively</em> constant. The body does not maintain
            perfectly fixed conditions — it allows small fluctuations around a target value
            (the set point) and responds when deviations become too large. Think of a
            thermostat: it does not maintain a perfectly constant room temperature, but
            triggers the heater when the room drops below a threshold and turns it off when
            the target is reached.
          </p>


          <!-- ── Why It Matters ── -->
          <h3>Why Does Homeostasis Matter?</h3>

          <div class="info-cards-row">
            <div class="info-card info-card--enzyme">
              <div class="info-card__icon">
                <svg width="42" height="42" viewBox="0 0 42 42" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <ellipse cx="21" cy="21" rx="14" ry="9" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" opacity="0.4"/>
                  <path d="M14 21 Q21 12 28 21" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="2" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <circle cx="21" cy="21" r="3" fill="var(--fluoro-cyan)" opacity="0.5"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
              <h4>Enzyme Function</h4>
              <p>
                Enzymes have optimal temperatures and pH ranges. Even small deviations cause
                conformational changes that reduce reaction rates — large deviations cause
                irreversible denaturation.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card info-card--cell">
              <div class="info-card__icon">
                <svg width="42" height="42" viewBox="0 0 42 42" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <circle cx="21" cy="21" r="14" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" opacity="0.35"/>
                  <circle cx="21" cy="21" r="6" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1" fill="none" opacity="0.5"/>
                  <circle cx="21" cy="21" r="2" fill="var(--green-vivid)" opacity="0.5"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
              <h4>Cell Health</h4>
              <p>
                Cells require precise osmotic conditions. Too much water and they lyse;
                too little and they crenate. Stable ion concentrations maintain resting
                membrane potential and signal transmission.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card info-card--survival">
              <div class="info-card__icon">
                <svg width="42" height="42" viewBox="0 0 42 42" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <path d="M21 8 L34 34 L8 34 Z" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" opacity="0.35"/>
                  <path d="M21 14 L29 30 L13 30 Z" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1" fill="none" opacity="0.4"/>
                  <circle cx="21" cy="26" r="2" fill="var(--fluoro-pink)" opacity="0.6"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
              <h4>Survival</h4>
              <p>
                Unchecked deviations from set points lead to physiological failure.
                Hyperthermia, hypoglycaemia, acidosis — these are conditions where
                homeostatic mechanisms have been overwhelmed.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="exam-tip">
            <h4>Assessment Tip</h4>
            <p>
              In your internal assessment report, every homeostatic explanation should link
              the regulated variable back to a biological consequence. Don't just say "body
              temperature is maintained at 37°C" — explain <em>why</em> that matters: enzyme
              function, metabolic rate, and cell survival all depend on it.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Set Points and Normal Ranges ── -->
          <h3>Set Points and Normal Ranges</h3>

          <p>
            A <strong>set point</strong> is the target value for a regulated variable — the
            value the body "aims for". However, the body does not maintain variables at a
            perfectly single value. Instead, it maintains them within a <strong>normal
            range</strong> around the set point. When the variable moves outside this range,
            corrective responses are triggered.
          </p>

          <div class="set-point-table-wrap">
            <table class="set-point-table">
              <caption>Normal ranges for key regulated variables in humans</caption>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Variable</th>
                  <th>Set Point</th>
                  <th>Normal Range</th>
                  <th>Condition if too low</th>
                  <th>Condition if too high</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Core body temperature</strong></td>
                  <td>37.0°C</td>
                  <td>36.1 – 37.2°C</td>
                  <td>Hypothermia</td>
                  <td>Hyperthermia / heat stroke</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Blood glucose</strong></td>
                  <td>~5 mmol/L</td>
                  <td>3.9 – 6.1 mmol/L (fasting)</td>
                  <td>Hypoglycaemia</td>
                  <td>Hyperglycaemia (diabetes)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Blood pH</strong></td>
                  <td>7.40</td>
                  <td>7.35 – 7.45</td>
                  <td>Acidosis</td>
                  <td>Alkalosis</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Plasma osmolarity</strong></td>
                  <td>290 mOsm/kg</td>
                  <td>285 – 295 mOsm/kg</td>
                  <td>Hypo-osmolarity (cell swelling)</td>
                  <td>Hyper-osmolarity (cell shrinkage)</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Key Terminology ── -->
          <h3>Key Terminology: The Components of Homeostasis</h3>

          <p>
            Every homeostatic mechanism involves the same set of functional components.
            You must be able to identify each component and explain its role for any
            homeostatic system.
          </p>

          <div class="terminology-grid">
            <div class="term-card term-card--stimulus">
              <div class="term-card__number">1</div>
              <h4>Stimulus</h4>
              <p>
                A change in a regulated variable that triggers the system. The stimulus
                is a <strong>deviation from the set point</strong> — it may be an increase
                or a decrease.
              </p>
              <div class="term-example">
                <span class="term-example__label">Example</span>
                Core body temperature rises above 37°C after exercise.
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="term-card term-card--receptor">
              <div class="term-card__number">2</div>
              <h4>Receptor (Sensor)</h4>
              <p>
                A structure that detects the stimulus and generates a signal proportional
                to the deviation. Receptors are <strong>specific</strong> — they respond
                to one type of change (e.g. temperature, not glucose).
              </p>
              <div class="term-example">
                <span class="term-example__label">Example</span>
                Thermoreceptors in the hypothalamus detect blood temperature directly.
                Peripheral thermoreceptors in the skin detect surface temperature.
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="term-card term-card--control">
              <div class="term-card__number">3</div>
              <h4>Control Centre (Integration Centre)</h4>
              <p>
                Receives the signal from the receptor, compares it to the set point, and
                determines the appropriate response. Often a region of the brain
                (hypothalamus) or a specialised organ.
              </p>
              <div class="term-example">
                <span class="term-example__label">Example</span>
                The hypothalamus integrates temperature signals and co-ordinates the
                body's cooling or warming responses.
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="term-card term-card--effector">
              <div class="term-card__number">4</div>
              <h4>Effector</h4>
              <p>
                The organ, gland, or muscle that carries out the corrective response.
                There may be <strong>multiple effectors</strong> acting in parallel to
                return the variable to the set point.
              </p>
              <div class="term-example">
                <span class="term-example__label">Example</span>
                Sweat glands (secrete sweat for evaporative cooling), blood vessels
                (vasodilation to increase heat loss at the skin surface).
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="term-card term-card--response">
              <div class="term-card__number">5</div>
              <h4>Response</h4>
              <p>
                The physiological change produced by the effector. The response
                <strong>opposes the original deviation</strong> — this is the defining
                feature of negative feedback.
              </p>
              <div class="term-example">
                <span class="term-example__label">Example</span>
                Sweating and vasodilation increase heat loss, returning core
                temperature toward 37°C.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="connection-box">
            <h4>Negative vs Positive Feedback</h4>
            <p>
              <strong>Negative feedback</strong> opposes the change that triggered it —
              it returns the variable toward the set point. This is the basis of
              homeostasis. <strong>Positive feedback</strong> amplifies the change — it
              is used for specific biological events that need to proceed to completion
              quickly (e.g. blood clotting, childbirth contractions, action potentials),
              but it does <em>not</em> maintain stable conditions. Almost all homeostatic
              mechanisms use negative feedback.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>


        <!-- ——————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————
             Interactive 1: Negative Feedback Loop Animation
             —————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— -->
        <section id="negative-feedback" class="content-section fade-in-up">
          <h2>Interactive: Negative Feedback Loop</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">
            Step through the negative feedback loop to see how each component connects.
            Click <strong>Next Step</strong> to advance, or jump to any component directly.
          </p>

          <div class="feedback-anim" id="feedback-anim" aria-live="polite">

            <!-- SVG Diagram -->
            <div class="feedback-anim__diagram">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 700 420" class="feedback-svg" role="img" aria-label="Negative feedback loop diagram showing stimulus, receptor, control centre, effector, and response">
                <defs>
                  <marker id="fb-arrow" markerWidth="10" markerHeight="7" refX="9" refY="3.5" orient="auto">
                    <polygon points="0 0, 10 3.5, 0 7" fill="var(--fluoro-cyan)" opacity="0.7"/>
                  </marker>
                  <marker id="fb-arrow-return" markerWidth="10" markerHeight="7" refX="9" refY="3.5" orient="auto">
                    <polygon points="0 0, 10 3.5, 0 7" fill="var(--green-vivid)" opacity="0.7"/>
                  </marker>
                  <filter id="glow-filter">
                    <feGaussianBlur stdDeviation="3" result="blur"/>
                    <feComposite in="SourceGraphic" in2="blur" operator="over"/>
                  </filter>
                </defs>

                <!-- Background boxes -->
                <!-- 1: Stimulus -->
                <rect id="fb-box-0" x="20" y="170" width="120" height="70" rx="10"
                  fill="var(--surface-2)" stroke="var(--border-subtle)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
                <text x="80" y="195" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-muted)" font-size="10" font-family="var(--font-mono)">STIMULUS</text>
                <text x="80" y="215" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="600">Deviation from</text>
                <text x="80" y="230" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="600">set point</text>

                <!-- Arrow 0→1 -->
                <line id="fb-arrow-01" x1="140" y1="205" x2="185" y2="205"
                  stroke="var(--border-subtle)" stroke-width="2" marker-end="url(#fb-arrow)" opacity="0.3"/>

                <!-- 2: Receptor -->
                <rect id="fb-box-1" x="195" y="170" width="120" height="70" rx="10"
                  fill="var(--surface-2)" stroke="var(--border-subtle)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
                <text x="255" y="195" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-muted)" font-size="10" font-family="var(--font-mono)">RECEPTOR</text>
                <text x="255" y="215" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="600">Detects change,</text>
                <text x="255" y="230" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="600">sends signal</text>

                <!-- Arrow 1→2 -->
                <line id="fb-arrow-12" x1="315" y1="205" x2="360" y2="205"
                  stroke="var(--border-subtle)" stroke-width="2" marker-end="url(#fb-arrow)" opacity="0.3"/>

                <!-- 3: Control Centre -->
                <rect id="fb-box-2" x="370" y="155" width="120" height="100" rx="10"
                  fill="var(--surface-2)" stroke="var(--border-subtle)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
                <text x="430" y="178" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-muted)" font-size="10" font-family="var(--font-mono)">CONTROL CENTRE</text>
                <text x="430" y="198" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="600">Compares to</text>
                <text x="430" y="213" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="600">set point,</text>
                <text x="430" y="228" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="600">determines response</text>
                <text x="430" y="245" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="600">(e.g. hypothalamus)</text>

                <!-- Arrow 2→3 -->
                <line id="fb-arrow-23" x1="490" y1="205" x2="535" y2="205"
                  stroke="var(--border-subtle)" stroke-width="2" marker-end="url(#fb-arrow)" opacity="0.3"/>

                <!-- 4: Effector -->
                <rect id="fb-box-3" x="545" y="170" width="120" height="70" rx="10"
                  fill="var(--surface-2)" stroke="var(--border-subtle)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
                <text x="605" y="195" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-muted)" font-size="10" font-family="var(--font-mono)">EFFECTOR</text>
                <text x="605" y="215" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="600">Carries out</text>
                <text x="605" y="230" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="600">correction</text>

                <!-- Arrow 3→Response (curve down and back) -->
                <path id="fb-arrow-34" d="M605 240 Q605 310 430 340 Q255 370 80 310 Q60 290 80 270"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--border-subtle)" stroke-width="2"
                  marker-end="url(#fb-arrow-return)" opacity="0.3"/>

                <!-- 5: Response / Back to Normal label -->
                <rect id="fb-box-4" x="20" y="320" width="120" height="60" rx="10"
                  fill="var(--surface-2)" stroke="var(--border-subtle)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
                <text x="80" y="342" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-muted)" font-size="10" font-family="var(--font-mono)">RESPONSE</text>
                <text x="80" y="360" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="600">Opposes change</text>
                <text x="80" y="375" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="10" font-family="var(--font-display)">(negative feedback)</text>

                <!-- "Back to normal" label at top -->
                <text id="fb-normal-label" x="350" y="40" text-anchor="middle"
                  fill="var(--green-vivid)" font-size="13" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="700" opacity="0">
                  Variable returns to set point
                </text>
                <line id="fb-normal-line" x1="200" y1="50" x2="500" y2="50"
                  stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="6 3" opacity="0"/>

                <!-- Step label (dynamic) -->
                <text id="fb-step-label" x="350" y="135" text-anchor="middle"
                  fill="var(--accent)" font-size="14" font-family="var(--font-display)" font-weight="700">
                  Click "Next Step" to begin
                </text>
              </svg>
            </div>

            <!-- Description panel -->
            <div class="feedback-anim__desc" id="fb-desc">
              <div class="fb-step-indicator">
                <span class="fb-step-dot" data-step="0"></span>
                <span class="fb-step-dot" data-step="1"></span>
                <span class="fb-step-dot" data-step="2"></span>
                <span class="fb-step-dot" data-step="3"></span>
                <span class="fb-step-dot" data-step="4"></span>
              </div>
              <p id="fb-desc-text" class="fb-desc-text">
                The negative feedback loop has five key components. Step through each one
                to see how they connect in a real homeostatic system.
              </p>
              <p id="fb-example-text" class="fb-example-text"></p>
            </div>

            <!-- Controls -->
            <div class="feedback-anim__controls">
              <button class="btn btn--secondary" id="fb-prev-btn" disabled>
                <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <path d="M13 8H3M7 4L3 8l4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                </svg>
                Previous
              </button>
              <button class="btn btn--primary" id="fb-next-btn">
                Next Step
                <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <path d="M3 8h10M9 4l4 4-4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                </svg>
              </button>
              <button class="btn btn--ghost" id="fb-reset-btn">
                Reset
              </button>
            </div>

            <!-- System selector -->
            <div class="feedback-anim__selector">
              <label class="fb-selector-label">Show example for:</label>
              <div class="fb-system-btns">
                <button class="fb-system-btn fb-system-btn--active" data-system="temperature">Temperature</button>
                <button class="fb-system-btn" data-system="glucose">Blood Glucose</button>
                <button class="fb-system-btn" data-system="osmoregulation">Osmoregulation</button>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>


        <!-- ——————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————
             Interactive 2: Set Point Visualiser
             —————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— -->
        <section id="set-point-vis" class="content-section fade-in-up">
          <h2>Interactive: Set Point Visualiser</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">
            Use the slider to change the <strong>external temperature</strong>. Watch how
            the body responds to maintain its core temperature set point of 37°C. Push
            the slider to the extremes to see what happens when the system is overwhelmed.
          </p>

          <div class="setpoint-vis" id="setpoint-vis">

            <!-- Slider control -->
            <div class="setpoint-vis__slider-row">
              <label class="setpoint-vis__label">External Temperature:</label>
              <div class="setpoint-vis__slider-wrap">
                <span class="setpoint-vis__min">−20°C</span>
                <input type="range" id="sp-slider" min="-20" max="60" value="20"
                  class="setpoint-vis__slider" aria-label="External temperature"/>
                <span class="setpoint-vis__max">60°C</span>
              </div>
              <span class="setpoint-vis__current-val" id="sp-ext-temp">20°C</span>
            </div>

            <!-- Main display -->
            <div class="setpoint-vis__display">

              <!-- Thermometer gauge -->
              <div class="setpoint-vis__gauge-wrap">
                <div class="gauge-label">Core Body Temperature</div>
                <div class="gauge-container" aria-live="polite">
                  <div class="gauge-track">
                    <div class="gauge-fill" id="sp-gauge-fill"></div>
                    <div class="gauge-setpoint" title="Set point: 37°C"></div>
                    <div class="gauge-zone gauge-zone--low" title="Danger: below 35°C"></div>
                    <div class="gauge-zone gauge-zone--high" title="Danger: above 40°C"></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="gauge-scale">
                    <span>34°C</span>
                    <span>35°C</span>
                    <span>36°C</span>
                    <span>37°C</span>
                    <span>38°C</span>
                    <span>39°C</span>
