          <!-- Reveal model answers -->
          <div class="activity-card" style="margin-top: var(--space-5);">
            <h4>Model Answers</h4>
            <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
              Attempt all questions before revealing.
            </p>
            <div class="reveal-section">
              <button class="reveal-btn" data-target="homeostasis-model-answers">
                <span class="reveal-btn__text">Show Model Answers</span>
                <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <path d="M4 6l4 4 4-4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                </svg>
              </button>
              <div class="reveal-content" id="homeostasis-model-answers" hidden>

                <div class="model-grade-section">
                  <h5 class="model-grade-label model-grade-label--achieved">Q1 — Achieved</h5>
                  <div class="answer-card">
                    Homeostasis is the process by which an organism maintains a relatively
                    stable internal environment despite changes in external conditions.
                    Physiological variables are kept within a normal range around a set point.
                    <br><br>
                    A <em>range</em> rather than a single value is maintained because it is
                    physiologically impossible to hold any variable at an absolutely fixed
                    point — the control mechanisms themselves take time to respond and overshoot
                    is inevitable. A range also allows the body to tolerate transient perturbations
                    (e.g. a meal, brief exercise) without triggering constant corrective responses.
                    The range defines the limits within which normal function is possible; deviations
                    beyond these limits trigger stronger corrective mechanisms.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="model-grade-section">
                  <h5 class="model-grade-label model-grade-label--merit">Q2 — Merit</h5>
                  <div class="answer-card">
                    <strong>Stimulus:</strong> Blood glucose rises above ~6 mmol/L after eating
                    (detected because glucose concentration in portal blood reaching the liver and
                    pancreas is elevated). <br>
                    <strong>Receptor:</strong> Beta cells of the islets of Langerhans in the
                    pancreas detect the elevated blood glucose directly. <br>
                    <strong>Control centre:</strong> Beta cells also act as the control centre —
                    they integrate the signal and secrete insulin. <br>
                    <strong>Effector:</strong> Body cells (liver, muscle, adipose tissue) respond
                    to insulin; liver and muscle cells in particular increase glucose uptake and
                    convert glucose to glycogen (glycogenesis). <br>
                    <strong>Response:</strong> Blood glucose concentration falls back toward the
                    set point (~5 mmol/L). As glucose falls, insulin secretion decreases —
                    this is the negative feedback loop.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="model-grade-section">
                  <h5 class="model-grade-label model-grade-label--merit">Q3 — Merit</h5>
                  <div class="answer-card">
                    <strong>(a)</strong> Negative feedback opposes the change that triggered it.
                    When a variable rises above the set point, the response acts to lower it;
                    when it falls below, the response acts to raise it. This restores the variable
                    to the set point, completing the feedback loop. It is "negative" because the
                    response is in the opposite direction to the deviation.
                    <br><br>
                    <strong>(b)</strong> Blood clotting (coagulation cascade) is a positive
                    feedback example: clotting factors activate more clotting factors, rapidly
                    amplifying the response until a clot forms. This cannot maintain stable
                    conditions because it does not oppose the change — it amplifies it. If used
                    for homeostasis, a small deviation would spiral into an uncontrolled extreme
                    rather than returning to the set point.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="model-grade-section">
                  <h5 class="model-grade-label model-grade-label--excellence">Q4 — Excellence</h5>
                  <div class="answer-card">
                    The student's claim underestimates the significance of pH regulation. While
                    it is true that extreme temperature deviations are immediately life-threatening,
                    a drop in blood pH from 7.4 to 7.3 (acidosis) has serious physiological
                    consequences. Hydrogen ions compete with calcium ions at troponin binding sites
                    in cardiac muscle, reducing contractility. Changes in H⁺ concentration alter
                    the charge distribution on proteins, causing conformational changes that reduce
                    enzyme activity — the same mechanism by which temperature deviation disrupts
                    enzymes. Acidosis also shifts the oxygen–haemoglobin dissociation curve (the
                    Bohr effect), impairing O₂ delivery to tissues. A pH of 7.3 represents a
                    more-than-doubled H⁺ concentration compared to pH 7.5 (logarithmic scale),
                    so even "small" numerical changes are biochemically large. Life-threatening
                    acidosis (pH below 7.2) can cause cardiac arrhythmias and coma.
                  </div>
                </div>

